#notmynonny kind of picture.  You can spot the grandpa and his niece on the left corner (down). He was talking and she was writing something in her notebook. Quite lovely scene isn't it? 
This brings back memories of my grandpa and our afternoon summer talks in the shade of the old cherry. 
We used to talk about everything  but the most fascinating were his stories about his life.
Let's say the funniest one is when he had to hide a carriage because he didn't want the communists to have it.( during collectivization/communism  peasants were forced to pay "tribute": animals, money....) He couldn't find a better place to hide it than to bury it close to the house and pretend that they are building a new room. In the end they decided to go on with the construction and even nowadays the carriage is buried  there ü§£.

So here it is again  #DublinHistoryMinute.
George's Street Arcade as it's commonly know today, it is Dublin's 1st purpose built Victorian Shopping Center .
Designed by British architects Lockwood& Mauson it was formally opened by the Lord Mayor in 1881 as the South City Markets.
On  August 27th 1892 a massive  fire devastated the whole building. After the fire there was a flood of public sympathy for the shopkeepers that lost everything and a fund for their relief was successfully organised. The Centre was re-built in the same style, using local labour and craftsmen and was re-opened on September 13th 1894.

Now , there are approximately fifty tenants varying in size from Dunnes Stores to small sidewalk stalls.
